echo "Static IP Configuration Using nmcli (StarFive Debian Setup)

    Show available network devices and identify the Ethernet interface:
    nmcli device status

    Delete old or broken profiles if needed (replace with actual names if different):
    sudo nmcli connection delete "Wired connection 1"
    sudo nmcli connection delete "Wired connection 2"

    Create a new static connection (replace end1 with your actual interface):
    sudo nmcli connection add type ethernet ifname end1 con-name star_net ipv4.addresses 192.168.50.56/24 ipv4.gateway 192.168.50.3 ipv4.dns "8.8.8.8 1.1.1.1" ipv4.method manual

    Activate the new connection:
    sudo nmcli connection up star_net

    Confirm assigned IP address:
    ip a

    Check DNS nameservers:
    cat /etc/resolv.conf
    You should see: nameserver 8.8.8.8 and nameserver 1.1.1.1

    Test raw internet connection:
    ping -c 4 8.8.8.8

    Test DNS resolution and full internet access:
    ping -c 4 google.com

Optional Cleanup (if /etc/network/interfaces was edited earlier)

Open the file:
sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces

Comment out any lines related to the Ethernet interface by adding # at the beginning of each line, for example:
auto end0
iface end0 inet static
address 192.168.50.56
netmask 255.255.255.0
gateway 192.168.50.3
dns-nameservers 8.8.8.8 1.1.1.1

Save and exit.

Enable NetworkManager to manage interfaces by editing:
sudo nano /etc/NetworkManager/NetworkManager.conf

Ensure it contains the following lines:
[main]
plugins=ifupdown,keyfile
[ifupdown]
managed=true

Restart the services:
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager
sudo systemctl restart networking

Then reboot:
sudo reboot

After reboot, run again:
nmcli device status
→ You should see the interface listed as “connected” or “disconnected” (not “unmanaged” or “unavailable”).
